When you look at a webpage, you see text, images, and buttons. But when JavaScript looks at a webpage, it sees a massive, highly organized family tree.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

DOM (Document Object Model)This tree is called the Document Object Model (DOM). It is the bridge between your JavaScript code and the HTML on the screen. If you want to change colors, read user input, or delete an item, you have to talk to the DOM.
We learn best when we look at the practice first and explore the theory later. Let us dive straight into the code and see exactly how JavaScript selects, traverses, creates, and destroys elements on a webpage.
1. The DOM Tree (How JavaScript Sees Your HTML)
When you write an HTML file, you are writing raw text. But JavaScript cannot understand raw text. To make your webpage interactive, the browser reads your HTML file from top to bottom and translates every single tag into a JavaScript Object (called a “Node”). It then connects all these nodes together into a tree structure.
The HTML Code: Imagine you have written this HTML file for a User Profile card:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Dashboard</title>
</head>
<body>
<div id="container">
<h1 id="title">User Profile</h1> <div class="card">
<img src="avatar.jpg" alt="Profile Photo" id="pic">
<p class="bio">Hello, I am a web developer.</p>
<ul class="skills">
<li class="skill-item">JavaScript</li>
<li class="skill-item">React</li>
</ul>
<button id="edit-btn">Edit Profile</button>
</div>
</div>
</body>
</html>
The DOM Tree: Here is exactly how JavaScript translates that specific HTML code into the DOM tree inside the computer’s memory. Notice how the HTML tags become elements, and the elements branch out into sub-elements and text!

The Theory:

• The Root: Everything lives inside the browser Window, which holds the Document.

• Element Nodes: Every single HTML tag (<body>, <ul>, <img>) becomes an Element Node.

• Text Nodes: The actual words on the screen (“User Profile”, “JavaScript”) are treated as separate child nodes living inside the Element Nodes.
Now that we know the structure, let us use JavaScript to manipulate it!
2. Selectors: Grabbing Elements from the Tree
Before you can change an element, you have to find it. Here is how we can grab the specific elements from our User Profile card.
The Practice:
// 1. Grab ONE element by its exact ID (Grabs the <h1>)
const mainTitle = document.getElementById('title');// 2. Grab ALL elements that share a class (Grabs both <li> tags)
const allSkills = document.getElementsByClassName('skill-item');
// 3. Grab ALL elements of a specific HTML tag (Grabs the <img>)
const allImages = document.getElementsByTagName('img');
// 4. Grab the FIRST element that matches a CSS selector (Grabs the <div class="card">)
const userCard = document.querySelector('.card');
// 5. Grab ALL elements that match a CSS selector (Grabs both <li> tags)
const everySkill = document.querySelectorAll('.skill-item');
The Theory:

• getElementById and querySelector are your precision tools. They hunt down exactly one element and hand it to you.

• getElementsByClassName, getElementsByTagName, and querySelectorAll act like nets. They scoop up every matching element on the page and group them together.
3. The Trap: NodeLists vs. HTMLCollections
When you grab our two list items (<li>), you might assume JavaScript gives you a standard Array. It does not!
The Practice:
// USING querySelectorAll (Returns a NodeList)
const nodeListSkills = document.querySelectorAll('.skill-item');// This works perfectly! We can loop through and highlight our skills.
nodeListSkills.forEach( (skill) => {
skill.style.backgroundColor = "yellow";
});
// USING getElementsByClassName (Returns an HTMLCollection)
const htmlCollectionSkills = document.getElementsByClassName('skill-item');
// ERROR! htmlCollectionSkills.forEach is not a function
/*
htmlCollectionSkills.forEach( (skill) => { ... } )
*/
// The Fix: Convert the HTMLCollection into a real Array first
const realArray = Array.from(htmlCollectionSkills);
realArray.forEach( (skill) => {
skill.style.color = "blue";
});
The Theory:

• querySelectorAll returns a NodeList. It looks like an array, and modern JavaScript allows you to use .forEach() on it directly.

• getElementsByClassName returns an HTMLCollection. This is an older, stricter data type that does not have .forEach(). To loop over it using modern methods, you must use Array.from() to convert it into a standard array first.
4. Traversing the DOM: Moving Up, Down, and Sideways
Sometimes you have an element, but you actually want its parent or its sibling. Let us walk around our Profile Card.
The Practice:
const myBio = document.querySelector('.bio');// Moving UP (Finding the parent: The <div class="card">)
const parentCard = myBio.parentElement;
// Moving DOWN (Finding children of the <ul>)
const skillList = document.querySelector('.skills');
const firstSkill = skillList.firstElementChild; // Grabs "JavaScript"
const allChildSkills = skillList.children;
// Moving SIDEWAYS (Finding siblings: Grabs the <ul> that comes after the <p>)
const nextElement = myBio.nextElementSibling;
The Theory: Every Node in the DOM is aware of its family. You can use properties like parentElement to climb up the tree, children to look inside an element, and nextElementSibling to jump to the next item on the exact same level.
5. Changing Content: innerText vs textContent vs innerHTML
Let us update the text inside our User Profile.
The Practice:
const bioText = document.querySelector('.bio');// 1. Changing plain text safely
bioText.innerText = "I am a Senior Web Developer!";
// 2. Reading all text (even if we hid it using CSS display: none)
console.log(bioText.textContent);
// 3. Injecting actual HTML tags to make it bold
bioText.innerHTML = "I am a <strong>Senior</strong> Web Developer!";
The Theory:

• innerText: Reads or writes the text exactly as a human sees it on the screen. It respects CSS (if text is hidden via CSS, innerText ignores it).

• textContent: Reads or writes all text inside the element, even if CSS is hiding it from the screen.

• innerHTML: The most powerful, but most dangerous. It allows you to inject actual HTML tags directly into the element. Never use innerHTML with input provided by a user, as it opens your site up to security vulnerabilities.
6. Changing Styles and Classes
Let us change the look of our “Edit Profile” button.
The Practice:
const button = document.getElementById('edit-btn');// Changing inline styles directly
button.style.backgroundColor = "green";
button.style.borderRadius = "5px";
// Adding, removing, and toggling CSS classes
button.classList.add('active');
button.classList.remove('hidden');
// Toggles are great for things like dark mode!
document.getElementById('container').classList.toggle('dark-theme');
The Theory: The style property lets you change CSS directly. Note that CSS properties like background-color become camelCase backgroundColor in JavaScript.
However, the professional way to style elements is using classList. Instead of writing messy inline CSS in your JavaScript, write your CSS classes in your stylesheet, and then use JavaScript to simply .add(), .remove(), or .toggle() those classes.
7. Manipulating Attributes
Let us update the user’s profile picture by changing the src attribute.
The Practice:
const profilePic = document.getElementById('pic');// Getting the current image link (avatar.jpg)
const currentLink = profilePic.getAttribute('src');
// Changing the image source to a new photo
profilePic.setAttribute('src', 'new-photo.jpg');
// Changing the alt text for accessibility
profilePic.setAttribute('alt', 'A photo of the Senior Developer');
The Theory: Attributes are the extra pieces of information inside an HTML tag (like src, href, alt, or disabled). getAttribute() reads the current value, setAttribute() updates it (or creates it if it is missing), and removeAttribute() deletes it.
8. Creating New Elements from Scratch
The user just learned a new skill! Let us add “Node.js” to their skills list.
The Practice:
// Step 1: Create an empty <li> element in memory
const newSkill = document.createElement('li');// Step 2: Customize it to match our other skills
newSkill.className = "skill-item";
newSkill.innerText = "Node.js";
// Step 3: Attach it to the webpage inside our <ul>
const skillList = document.querySelector('.skills');
skillList.appendChild(newSkill);
The Theory: First, createElement builds the raw HTML tag in the computer's memory. Second, you customize it. Finally, you use appendChild to glue it onto the DOM tree, placing it as the very last child of whichever parent you targeted (in this case, placing it at the bottom of the <ul>).
9. Editing and Removing Elements
The user is done editing their profile, so let us remove the Edit button.
The Practice:
// EDITING: Replacing an old element with a new one
const oldTitle = document.getElementById('title');
const newTitle = document.createElement('h1');
newTitle.innerText = "Jane Doe's Profile";
newTitle.id = "title";
oldTitle.parentElement.replaceChild(newTitle, oldTitle);
// REMOVING: Deleting an element completely
const button = document.getElementById('edit-btn');
button.remove();The Theory: To swap an entire element structure, create the new element and use replaceChild. To delete an element entirely, simply select it and call .remove(). The browser instantly snips it out of the DOM tree.
Summary
The DOM is just a translation of your HTML into JavaScript Objects. By mastering the differences between NodeLists and HTMLCollections, traversing the family tree, and using methods like createElement and classList, you have complete control over what happens on the screen. Start opening the developer console on your favorite websites and practice selecting and removing elements—it is the best way to see the DOM in action!
